04568nam a22005655i 9780228002925DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280029257 a10.1515/97802280029252doi  a(DE-B1597)655367  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aP119.3b.L364 2020 7aPHI0380002bisacsh04a306.44922300aLanguage Ethics /ced. by Yael Peled, Daniel M. Weinstock. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource :b3 diagrams, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Idea of Language Ethics as a Field of Inquiry -- tWhat Is (or “Are”) Language Ethics? -- tLanguage: Rights and Claims -- tLanguage Ethics -- tOperationalizing “Diversity” for Language Policy -- tIntralinguistic Justice -- tLiberalism and Language Policy in “Mere Number Cases” -- tLanguage Policy, Political Theory, and English as a “Global” Language -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLanguage is central to political philosophy, yet until now there has been little in the way of a common framework capable of bridging disciplines that share an interest in language, power, and ethics. Studies are predominantly carried out in isolated disciplinary silos - notably linguistics, philosophy, political science, public administration, and education. This volume proposes a new vision for understanding the political ethics of language, particularly in linguistically diverse societies, and it establishes the necessary common framework for this field of inquiry: language ethics. Through creative and constructive thinking, Language Ethics considers how to advance our understanding of the human commonalities of moral and linguistic capacities and the challenge of linguistic difference and societal interdependence. The book embraces the longstanding centrality of language to moral reasoning and reinterprets it in a manner that draws on the social and political life of real-world inter- and intralinguistic issues. Contributors to this collection are leading international experts from different disciplines and approaches whose voices add diverse insight to the discourse on ethics and language justice. Exploring social, political, and economic realities, Language Ethics illuminates the complex nexus between ethics and language and highlights the contemporary challenges facing multilingual societies, including the uncertainties, ambiguities, anxieties, and hopes that accompany them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLanguage policy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Language.2bisacsh1 aAvnon, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrin, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeled, Yael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeled, Yael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRicento, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobichaud, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchutter, Helder De, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeinstock, Daniel M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeinstock, Daniel M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228002925?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228002925423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228002925/original  aGBV-deGruyter-a